# Agile workflow for Linear tickets

## Context

Apply this rule when the user asks the agent to work on a ticket, for example:
- "please work on DB-86"
- "pick up DB-123"
- "can you take DB-10?"

In this organisation, tickets are defined in Linear and are usually prefixed with `DB-`.

## Requirements

- **Single ticket focus**: Work on exactly one ticket at a time, aiming for a potentially releasable outcome before starting any other ticket.
- **Ticket lookup**: When a user references a ticket ID (for example `DB-86`), look up the ticket in Linear via MCP and use its title/description/acceptance criteria as the source of truth for scope.
- **Eligibility check**: Before starting work, verify the ticket is in the **Todo** column/state. If it is not, do not start implementation; instead, explain the mismatch and ask for the intended next step.
- **Move to in progress**: When starting work, move the ticket to **In Progress** in Linear.
- **Implementation discipline**: Keep changes scoped to the ticket; avoid unrelated refactors, drive-by cleanups, or picking up additional tickets.
- **Completion**: When the work is done and ready for review, move the ticket to **In Review** in Linear.
- **Completion comment**: Leave a Linear comment summarizing what was done and which files were modified.
- **MCP reliability**: If the Linear MCP call fails or times out, retry once. If it still fails, ask the user to provide the ticket title/description (or a screenshot/paste) and proceed using that, explicitly noting the limitation in the Linear comment once connectivity is restored.

## Examples

<example>
User: "Please work on DB-86"
Assistant actions:
- Fetch DB-86 from Linear
- Confirm it is in Todo
- Move DB-86 to In Progress
- Implement the ticket end-to-end
- Move DB-86 to In Review
- Comment on DB-86 with summary + files changed
</example>

<example type="invalid">
User: "Please work on DB-86"
Assistant actions:
- Starts coding immediately without checking Linear
- Works on DB-86 and also picks up DB-90 in the same session
- Finishes DB-86 but forgets to move it to In Review or leave a comment
</example>

<critical>
 - ALWAYS fetch the referenced ticket from Linear before implementing
 - ALWAYS move the ticket to In Progress when starting and In Review when done
 - NEVER work on multiple tickets at the same time
</critical>
